<h2>Tutorial 27. Adding a Modesty Flap, Grommets and Cross-Back Straps. </h2>
<h2>A Possible Version of a Fastener. </h2>
<p></p>
<p><strong>I start sewing a modesty flap. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I have cut rectangles out of organza and lace. </strong>I put them together so that the face side of the lace is at the top. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image002.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>The length of these rectangles equals the length of the back plus seam allowances at the top and down the bottom, i.e. another 2.5cm. The width is arbitrary. Each rectangle should be folded in half. Mine are 10cm wide when ready. I don’t try to be too precise when sewing this modesty flap since it is hidden inside and performs no particularly important functions. </p>
<p><strong>If you’re worried that the lace might slide off the organza while you’re sewing, you can secure it but only along the vertical edge. Don’t forget this! </strong>This is relevant not only in terms of sewing corsets. It concerns any fabric you will ever need to join. For example if you want to duplicate all pieces of an evening dress with lace, then you should join the lace and the main pieces solely along their vertical edges. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image004.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I fold the piece in half and join it along its top and bottom ends. </strong>I even out the seam allowances. The fabrics are transparent and the seam allowances will show through. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image006.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>Then I stitch along the open side leaving a small hole for turning it out. </strong>You can also trim the corners. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image008.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>And I turn it out. Please note the way I turn out its corners! </strong>Experienced seamstresses are familiar with this method but newbies will find it very useful. </p>
<p><strong>I put my finger at the very corner, push the seam allowance in and place my nail right at this spot. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image010.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>And I start turning it out right over my nail. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image012.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>It comes out perfect. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image014.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>The task is harder when you deal with thicker corners with more seam allowances. </strong>I move my fingers as if I were washing them after turning them out. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image016.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>Here it is. You can bring it to perfection with the help of a needle if you need. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image018.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>Now I can iron the flap but before doing so <strong>I shall stitch up the hole I left for turning it out. </strong>The flap is thin so the hole is rather small. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image020.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image022.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>The modesty flap is ready! </strong>I simply need to iron it. It will be sewn onto the inside of the corset along the side where I had a hole. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image024.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>Now I will mark the location of eyelets for the lacing and insert them using a hand press machine. </strong></p>
<p><strong>I measure the length of the area where eyelets should be located. </strong>I got 28cm and the intervals between the holes will be 3.5cm. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image026.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I punch holes through according to the markings on the first side of the corset. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image028.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>And then I transfer the location of the holes onto the other side of the corset. </strong>I put the other lacing bar with its face side up, cover it with the bar that has holes on it, match their edges accurately and mark the location of holes to achieve perfect symmetry between grommets on both sides of the corset. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image030.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image032.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I punch holes through. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image034.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I insert metal eyelets into the holes and prepare washers. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image036.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I put a top setting die onto the hand press machine and insert the washers. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image038.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>Don’t forget to check their quality. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image040.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I repeat the same procedure with the other side of the corset. </strong></p>
<p><strong>And then I pin the modesty flap at the edge of one lacing bar across its whole length and sew it on by hand with blind stitches. </strong>Some people make a machine stitch over the organza but I don’t like it. I prefer making neat and pretty hand stitches. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image042.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>And this is what the straps look like when fully finished with lace. </strong>I used fusible web for securing the lace. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image044.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p></p>
<p><strong>I will mark a suitable length of the straps during a fit test, fold them back and add a clasp. </strong>And then I will trim the edges and give them a clean finish. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image046.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>There is one more important issue we need to look into: how to make bridges on this kind of a deep front V-cut? </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image048.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>You can make a bridge out of a fabric strap with a pencil-edge finish that you stitch up and turn out. Mark the location of bridges with pins. <strong>It is necessary to make one bridge at the bust level or under the bust! </strong>The rest is optional. I know it from my own experience that when you tighten a corset on a girl, the body often tends to bulge out from the cut. You should cover this spot with some mesh or organza. But I have decided to use a couple of bridges instead. </p>
<p><strong>Here is another interesting trick. </strong>The ends of these bridges will be seen through fabric which means we can’t leave them as is. But if we simply trim them, they might not stay robust enough. <strong>I have found a good way out: I shorten these ends and catch them up with a stitch. </strong>This way the bridges stay reliable and their ends don’t stick out. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image050.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>Our corset is almost ready. </strong>During the last fit test my team was preparing for shooting a video to demonstrate you the finished garment. I wanted to determine the spot for adding a clasp to the straps when the corset was on Kate. But when she put the corset on, I found making a plain clasp somewhat “unimaginative". </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image052.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I felt like varying the design, making it more interesting and showing you the potential of this pattern and this corset model. </strong></p>
<p><strong>What was my idea? </strong>Instead of joining the straps behind the neck I decided to make cross-back straps. This is a frequently used type of straps and my clients often ask for it! </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image054.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>However a certain issue always arises in this situation: how to secure such straps at the back? </strong></p>
<p>It seems as easy as pie! We’ll just make these straps longer, arrange them in a criss-cross manner and fasten them somewhere at the back. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image056.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>But it is more challenging than that! </strong>You could sew the straps together tightly so that the client would put the corset on by pulling the straps over her head. This usually has a negative influence upon the fit of the corset. First of all, the straps should always be somewhat tense and the corset will definitely “jump up" if your client doesn’t hold it firmly at the waistline when she wears it! The fit and the balance of the garment get distorted. And then women usually put such garments on with make-up and a fancy hair-do already on. Now imagine that your client with lipstick, eye-shadows and blush on her face and with beautifully done hair has to somehow squeeze through a rather small opening! This is sure quite a bad idea! </p>
<p><strong>So the following question is always important: how to leave the straps open for now and then manage to secure them on our finished corset? </strong></p>
<p><strong>We have come up with a great idea for Kate, my daughter-in-law and my client, and you can most likely use this idea, too! Here!</strong> Instead of shortening the original length of the straps I have folded the seam allowance by about 1.5cm and stitched a ribbon folded in half to it. This is the same kind of a ribbon I use for lacing the corset. The length of this ribbon is optional – mine is 25cm when folded or 50cm at full length. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image058.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>Then I have sewn a loop out of a pencil-edge fabric strap onto the corset with one end at the side seam and the other at the princess seam of the back. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image060.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I have sewn this loop on by hand using whip stitches. </strong>It will hold the strap very well. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image062.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>This is our idea: put the strap through the loop and tie a bow! </strong>That’s how simple it is! There are three bows at the top of the back: one bow from the lacing and two bows from the straps. Putting such a corset on is very easy! Feel free to use my idea or invent your own interesting version of a fastener for cross-back straps. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image064.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>I would like to point it out again: this model is in great demand and very popular among my clients. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Here are a few pictures of the ready corset:</strong></p>
<p></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image066.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image068.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image070.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/Transparent_corsets/corset_2/Tutorial%2027_files/image072.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>

